    <h2>Red Wine</h2>
    <p>In general, the more intense and tasty a dish is, the stronger a wine should be. To accompany game or lamb, for instance, a full-bodied wine will do. Lighter wines will harmonize with foods of similar intensity, such as white meats, poultry, pasta with tomato or rosée sauces, and fish, such as salmon. Medium-bodied wines are versatile. The more fruity ones will harmonize with pasta and meat sauce, and sausages; others, with a more woody, spicy profile, will bring out the best in grilled beef and semi-strong cheeses.</p>
